contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:37.737 --> 00:40.228
Technically, what happened wasn't my fault.

00:40.306 --> 00:41.398
I'm a minor.

00:41.474 --> 00:44.773
I'm not responsible
for my actions... technically.

00:51.051 --> 00:52.712
- Where are you going?
- Running away. What does it look like?

00:52.786 --> 00:54.447
- We gotta stick with the plan.
- No!

00:54.554 --> 00:58.251
But these things should be taken
on a case-by-case basis.

00:58.324 --> 01:01.589
In our case, I've always
been the responsible party.

01:01.661 --> 01:04.289
- We gotta get out of here.
- Stick with the plan.

01:04.397 --> 01:05.625
Oh, God.

01:08.301 --> 01:10.462
Someone had to look out for him.

01:15.608 --> 01:17.235
Welcome to McDonald's.

01:17.310 --> 01:19.938
Can I have a Number 1?

01:20.013 --> 01:22.504
Actually, can I have
a five-piece chicken?

01:22.615 --> 01:24.776
Um, but instead of the Coke

01:24.851 --> 01:26.944
I want a McFlurry
with extra Oreos,

01:27.020 --> 01:28.510
and make sure
they stir it in.

01:28.621 --> 01:32.284
And then a Number 1 with mustard, ketchup...

01:32.358 --> 01:34.019
Pickles and lettuce only.

01:34.127 --> 01:37.528
When my father went away,
I lived alone in our house.

01:37.630 --> 01:43.034
Which was not exactly normal,
but at least I had a routine.

01:46.005 --> 01:50.305
Before, when he was home,
I could never exactly get comfortable

01:50.376 --> 01:55.313
because it always felt like
something was about to happen.

02:50.703 --> 02:52.694
What?

02:52.772 --> 02:54.262
Oh, yeah,
it was so weird,

02:54.374 --> 02:56.706
I don't know whether
I dreamt it, you know,

02:56.776 --> 02:59.108
or heard it on the news.

02:59.212 --> 03:03.546
Naked Chinese men
washing ashore by the dozens

03:03.616 --> 03:07.575
up and down
Southern California beaches

03:07.687 --> 03:09.917
at sunrise.

03:11.791 --> 03:13.258
Boat people, you know?

03:13.359 --> 03:16.726
The boat stops outside
the maritime limit,

03:16.796 --> 03:18.889
they put their clothes
in plastic bags,

03:18.965 --> 03:22.867
and they swim ashore.

03:22.936 --> 03:25.234
Naked Chinese guys.

03:25.305 --> 03:27.102
Fuckin' amazing.

03:30.710 --> 03:33.440
Naked Chinese guys?

03:33.546 --> 03:35.309
Jesus Christ.

03:35.415 --> 03:37.906
Don't people go to hospitals
to get better?

04:01.808 --> 04:05.471
It would've been easier
if we'd just sold the house,

04:05.578 --> 04:06.909
because the way
the market was,

04:06.980 --> 04:08.572
we would've cleaned up.

04:08.648 --> 04:11.014
But Charlie grew up
in our house;

04:11.117 --> 04:12.584
he refused to leave.

04:13.786 --> 04:16.310
Even though we were
barely getting by.

04:20.827 --> 04:23.921
Before I was born, he had
already lived several lives

04:23.997 --> 04:26.659
and managed to avoid
fatherhood for a lot of years.

04:27.800 --> 04:30.792
I'm pretty sure my arrival
took him by surprise.

04:39.178 --> 04:42.636
Once, when things went south
for Charlie in Saint Louis,

04:42.715 --> 04:44.706
he had to pawn that bass.

04:44.817 --> 04:47.945
He said that everything
really started to go wrong after that.

04:48.021 --> 04:51.115
And they didn't start going right again
until he found it two years later

04:51.190 --> 04:53.658
in a pawn shop in Atlanta.

04:53.726 --> 04:56.854
He said things were
all right after that,

04:56.963 --> 04:59.523
all evidence to the contrary.

05:25.658 --> 05:26.852
Oh, shit!

05:42.075 --> 05:43.599
What's going on?

05:43.710 --> 05:46.440
Great things.

05:46.546 --> 05:48.776
So, it was time to get back

05:48.881 --> 05:51.076
on that ol' bipolar
pony and ride.

05:51.184 --> 05:54.381
Naked Chinese guys.
Hee hee hee!

06:08.234 --> 06:10.725
Pepper and Charlie spent
years together on the road

06:10.803 --> 06:13.897
with a five-piece jazz combo.

06:13.973 --> 06:17.602
Once, after a club date
on the Kentucky side of Cincinnati,

06:17.710 --> 06:20.543
Pepper ate so many pancakes
at a Denny's that the busboys

06:20.613 --> 06:23.446
had to unbolt the table
to get him out of the booth.

06:24.984 --> 06:27.418
Hey-hey,
lookin' good, man.

06:29.288 --> 06:30.949
Lost some weight.

06:31.057 --> 06:32.752
It's the chemo.

06:32.825 --> 06:35.385
Oh.

06:35.461 --> 06:37.554
Hey, might as well
put that away.

06:37.630 --> 06:38.995
I'm not playing anymore.

06:39.098 --> 06:41.760
Some other time.

06:41.834 --> 06:43.768
I'm not doing that,
either.

06:43.836 --> 06:48.102
Oh, it's a whole new
Charlie.

06:48.174 --> 06:51.302
- Hello, Miranda.
- Hey, Pepper.

06:51.411 --> 06:53.276
How are you, sweetie?

06:59.285 --> 07:00.752
What the hell is that?

07:01.988 --> 07:04.923
It's my uniform.

07:04.991 --> 07:06.458
You got a job?

07:08.361 --> 07:09.851
Aren't you supposed
to be in school?

07:09.962 --> 07:11.827
No, wait. Wait a minute.
Wait a minute.

07:11.931 --> 07:13.523
Is this Christmastime?

07:15.301 --> 07:17.428
It's March.

07:17.503 --> 07:19.300
Oh.

07:19.372 --> 07:22.000
Well, then, why aren't
you in school?

07:22.108 --> 07:24.201
I had to give
school up, Charlie.

07:24.310 --> 07:25.641
I had to make money,
you know,

07:25.711 --> 07:27.838
while you were gone
for two years.

07:28.714 --> 07:29.703
Huh.

07:29.816 --> 07:32.046
I'll be back around 10.

07:32.151 --> 07:33.709
You working at night?

07:33.820 --> 07:35.219
Yeah.
I gotta go.

07:35.321 --> 07:37.118
Wait, wait,
you working at night?

07:37.190 --> 07:39.988
I mean, that's not good.
It's not a safe place. I don't like that.

07:40.059 --> 07:41.822
It's not the old McDonald's
on Alameda.

07:41.894 --> 07:43.452
It's a new one
on Crest Parkway.

07:43.896 --> 07:45.363
Crest Parkway.

07:45.465 --> 07:48.662
Some new neighborhood,
Tierra Buena Estates.

07:48.734 --> 07:49.666
I don't know.

07:49.735 --> 07:52.203
Where the fuck is that?

07:52.305 --> 07:54.034
Hey, can I get a ride
from you tomorrow?

07:54.140 --> 07:56.700
I gotta see a man about a job.

07:56.809 --> 07:58.208
No way.

07:58.311 --> 08:00.711
I got an interview.

08:02.014 --> 08:03.982
Yeah, sure,
I'll give you a ride.

08:10.590 --> 08:14.082
You make me laugh.

08:14.193 --> 08:16.855
When Charlie was in the mental hospital,

08:16.929 --> 08:19.363
Social Services thought
I was with my mother.

08:19.432 --> 08:22.560
And Child Welfare thought
I was with my father.

08:22.668 --> 08:24.533
My father thought
I was with my mother.

08:24.604 --> 08:27.004
My mother thought
I was with a foster family.

08:27.073 --> 08:31.169
Somewhere, some foster family
thought I was with my father, and so on.

08:31.244 --> 08:33.006
Welcome to McDonald's.

08:33.078 --> 08:35.876
By working double shifts
and keeping expenses low,

08:35.948 --> 08:39.679
I was able to buy
a car on Ebay.

08:39.751 --> 08:41.845
They didn't know
who they were selling it to.

08:41.921 --> 08:44.116
An unlicensed 15-year-old
looks the same

08:44.222 --> 08:46.191
as everyone else on Ebay.

08:46.259 --> 08:48.591
It's like the Social Services thing,

08:48.694 --> 08:50.559
nobody sees anybody.

08:52.865 --> 08:54.856
I admit, it's a beater...

08:56.869 --> 08:58.200
...but a safe beater.

09:03.709 --> 09:07.110
Things were a lot different
when Charlie was gone.

09:07.213 --> 09:09.374
Easier.

09:09.448 --> 09:12.474
In some ways,
things were wonderful.

09:21.794 --> 09:24.388
You always get home so late?

09:24.463 --> 09:26.897
It's none of your
business, Charlie.

09:26.966 --> 09:29.662
Why don't you try
calling me "Dad"?

10:14.981 --> 10:19.509
Animals were popping up
in the most unlikely places.

10:19.619 --> 10:21.314
Someone from work
said she saw a deer

10:21.387 --> 10:23.651
in the cosmetics aisle at Target.

10:33.633 --> 10:35.396
You have an interview here?

10:39.238 --> 10:42.537
I'm having a hard time
picturing you working here.

10:51.684 --> 10:53.652
I thought you said
the interview was at 3.

11:07.900 --> 11:09.527
Good luck!

11:15.841 --> 11:19.208
After Mom left,
Charlie helped me

11:19.278 --> 11:21.746
with my class projects.

11:21.847 --> 11:27.683
He did his best, but things
changed for me at school.

11:27.753 --> 11:31.052
He had his own ideas
about science and history.

11:31.123 --> 11:33.250
When the teachers
disagreed with those ideas,

11:33.359 --> 11:35.725
he always told them
they could look it up.

11:35.795 --> 11:37.387
You think they're
going to like it?

11:37.463 --> 11:38.953
They're going to love it.

11:39.065 --> 11:41.625
- Think so?
- I know so.

11:43.302 --> 11:44.564
You have a good day,
sweetie.

11:44.637 --> 11:45.797
- Okay.
- Okay.

11:47.073 --> 11:49.132
Good, very nice, Ron.

11:49.241 --> 11:51.300
That's fine.

11:54.980 --> 11:57.778
Who are the little people, Miranda?

11:57.883 --> 12:00.374
Those are the bodies
of the Chumash Indians

12:00.453 --> 12:02.887
who died of syphilis
and influenza,

12:02.955 --> 12:06.254
infected by the missionaries.

12:06.325 --> 12:09.123
Uh, Miranda,
go out in the hallway

12:09.228 --> 12:11.389
and wait for me
out there.

12:11.464 --> 12:12.453
Go on.

12:17.403 --> 12:18.563
I don't understand.

12:18.637 --> 12:20.969
We're not having
any interviews.

12:21.073 --> 12:23.268
We're not hiring now.

12:24.677 --> 12:27.009
Okay, sorry.
Thanks.

12:27.113 --> 12:30.742
Proceed to route.

12:30.816 --> 12:35.014
- Left turn in two miles.
- Charlie!

12:35.121 --> 12:36.520
- Goodbye.
- Shit, Charlie...

12:36.622 --> 12:38.351
Hey, Miranda. Hi.

12:38.457 --> 12:39.583
Where did you go?

12:39.658 --> 12:41.250
Just, you know,
walking around,

12:41.327 --> 12:42.851
checking
the neighborhood out.

12:42.962 --> 12:45.795
What about the job?

12:45.865 --> 12:49.096
You know why people
like to eat in this place?

12:49.168 --> 12:51.830
Fear of the unknown.

12:51.937 --> 12:54.098
Nothing in there
surprises them.

12:54.173 --> 12:56.471
Why do you feel like
you have to make stuff up?

12:56.542 --> 12:58.669
I mean, so you're not
looking for a job.

12:58.778 --> 13:00.643
You just want to go,
I don't know,

13:00.713 --> 13:02.010
explore or something.

13:02.114 --> 13:03.376
That's fine, whatever.

13:03.482 --> 13:05.643
I mean, it would be great
if you got a job.

13:05.718 --> 13:07.481
I was barely scraping by
when it was just me...

13:07.553 --> 13:08.645
Pull over there.

13:08.721 --> 13:10.382
You have arrived.

13:10.489 --> 13:12.855
You know what, no.
I just wasted half my afternoon.

13:12.958 --> 13:14.016
Please, just pull in right over there.

13:14.126 --> 13:17.152
No, I'm not letting you
out of this car.

13:17.229 --> 13:18.526
Miranda, I gotta go.

13:18.631 --> 13:20.690
What are you talking about?
What is this all about?

13:20.800 --> 13:22.358
- Just tell me what you're doing.
- It's embarrassing, okay?

13:22.468 --> 13:25.960
I take these medications.
I gotta do pit stops all the time.

13:27.706 --> 13:29.196
Yeah. I'm sorry.

13:34.180 --> 13:36.580
Can you back up to the bushes?

13:47.993 --> 13:53.397
When possible, make the first
available legal U-turn.

14:26.432 --> 14:28.093
Charlie?

15:39.872 --> 15:42.033
Ow! Shit!

15:42.141 --> 15:45.042
Charlie? You okay?

15:45.144 --> 15:46.975
I'm fine.

15:47.046 --> 15:48.877
Stop! Stop!

15:48.981 --> 15:50.278
God...

15:50.349 --> 15:53.147
What are you doing?
Do you have to do this right now?

15:53.218 --> 15:55.277
The stars are
in a perfect position.

15:55.354 --> 15:57.049
They won't be like this
for another year.

15:59.558 --> 16:01.287
I can't stop you, can I?

16:05.831 --> 16:08.698
Work your magic.

16:17.810 --> 16:20.210
Oh, yeah, that's it,
the northerly declination

16:20.312 --> 16:21.506
from Sirius the Dog Star.

16:21.580 --> 16:23.047
That's my baby!

16:35.995 --> 16:37.986
This is it.

16:38.063 --> 16:39.655
This is what?

16:42.001 --> 16:43.263
What're you doing?

16:43.369 --> 16:44.529
Come on, let's go.

16:44.603 --> 16:45.592
Come on.

16:56.448 --> 16:59.008
Oh, come on.

17:08.527 --> 17:10.688
Come on,
I'll give you a boost.

17:10.762 --> 17:12.753
Come here.

17:23.809 --> 17:25.571
Just so you know,
I have to be at work

17:25.644 --> 17:27.202
in, like, seven hours.

17:27.279 --> 17:30.112
Relax.
You'll be there.

17:33.619 --> 17:35.610
Miranda...

17:35.721 --> 17:38.747
meet the Excalibur 1000.

17:40.726 --> 17:42.091
Is that a metal detector?

17:51.737 --> 17:52.999
Now you hear that?

17:53.105 --> 17:56.097
That's maybe tin foil or nickel.

17:56.175 --> 17:59.633
Nickels and tin foil
make that low tone.

17:59.745 --> 18:04.011
We call that the fool's gold
of modern prospecting.

18:04.116 --> 18:05.140
Prospecting?

18:05.250 --> 18:06.945
Yeah.

18:10.355 --> 18:12.687
High tone,
could be silver.

18:12.791 --> 18:15.089
Silver is a great conductor.

18:22.468 --> 18:25.266
Must be one
of the old quarters.

18:25.337 --> 18:27.862
The new ones,
they don't have much silver in them.

18:29.775 --> 18:32.107
We are well on our way
to paying off the Visa.

18:36.181 --> 18:37.307
You know, Charlie,
the manual says

18:37.382 --> 18:38.872
you can plug headphones
into that thing,

18:38.984 --> 18:41.043
so why don't you do that
so that we don't get popped?

18:41.153 --> 18:43.383
No, then you wouldn't
get to hear it

18:43.489 --> 18:44.478
when it makes a noise.

18:48.861 --> 18:49.850
Huh!

18:55.801 --> 18:57.166
Get the shovel!

18:57.236 --> 18:59.033
- We have a shovel?
- It's in the bag!

18:59.138 --> 19:02.005
I'm am out of here.
We're going to get busted.

19:02.074 --> 19:03.666
We're not doing
anything illegal.

19:03.742 --> 19:04.868
This is public land.

19:04.977 --> 19:06.205
There's gotta be
something illegal about...

19:06.311 --> 19:07.869
You are so lame,
Miranda.

19:07.980 --> 19:10.210
I can't believe I raised
such a law-abiding citizen.

19:10.315 --> 19:11.748
Oh, you raised me?

19:11.850 --> 19:15.377
Of course,
the highest tone

19:15.487 --> 19:18.888
is for the best conductor of them all.

19:44.950 --> 19:47.180
Eureka.

19:48.287 --> 19:50.016
Can we go now?

19:50.088 --> 19:54.286
Don't you want to
even know what this is?

19:55.794 --> 19:57.728
Okay.

19:57.796 --> 20:00.458
What is it?

20:00.566 --> 20:03.865
This is a doubloon.

20:03.936 --> 20:05.028
A what?

20:05.103 --> 20:09.870
A doubloon
from the 17th century.

20:14.279 --> 20:18.045
The diary of Father
Juan Florismartes Torres,

20:18.116 --> 20:21.108
1651.

20:21.220 --> 20:26.055
So, I picked up this book
in the hospital library

20:26.124 --> 20:27.557
and it got me thinking.

20:27.626 --> 20:29.389
I thought the whole idea
behind the hospital

20:29.461 --> 20:31.258
was for you
to stop thinking.

20:31.330 --> 20:33.127
And I got some other books.

20:33.232 --> 20:35.393
More books, eh?

20:36.668 --> 20:42.072
Along with a gold crucifix
and the statue of the Virgin,

20:42.140 --> 20:47.806
Father Torres' expedition
had a cache of gold doubloons.

20:47.913 --> 20:52.646
Now, these doubloons were dated.

20:54.486 --> 20:58.286
This one...
it's hard to see.

20:58.357 --> 21:01.815
Something...
Something, 1624.

21:01.927 --> 21:03.451
Let me see.

21:06.164 --> 21:08.496
That's 24 carats.

21:14.773 --> 21:17.970
Records that I obtained from
the Spanish Treasury indicate...

21:18.043 --> 21:19.203
Okay. Wait, wait, wait.

21:19.311 --> 21:21.370
How the hell
did you obtain records

21:21.480 --> 21:23.710
from the Spanish Treasury
from a mental institution?

21:23.815 --> 21:24.804
The internet.

21:24.883 --> 21:26.874
- Perfect.
- No, I'll show you.

21:26.985 --> 21:28.111
Here.

21:36.862 --> 21:38.659
See for yourself.

21:38.730 --> 21:42.166
Father Torres' doubloons
were dated.

21:42.234 --> 21:45.863
Now, coins minted in 1624
were allocated

21:45.971 --> 21:47.905
for what we call now,
you know, "petty cash,"

21:48.006 --> 21:50.065
which Torres lost sooner.

21:50.175 --> 21:53.235
Nobody else was around back then,
so it's gotta be his.

21:53.345 --> 21:55.142
Now based upon
where we found this

21:55.213 --> 21:57.238
and the reports of
the underground cave system...

21:57.349 --> 21:59.180
- Cave system?
- Right. Right.

21:59.251 --> 22:01.014
So all we gotta do
is follow this journal

22:01.086 --> 22:04.055
and it's going to lead us
to the treasure.

22:05.657 --> 22:08.524
It's just...
It's waiting to be found.

22:09.995 --> 22:12.555
You're serious.

22:12.664 --> 22:13.892
Yeah.

22:13.999 --> 22:16.194
Look, a lot of people
must've read this journal.

22:16.501 --> 22:18.025
How come nobody ever found
the treasure before?

22:18.103 --> 22:20.401
They've tried!
I mean, lots of people have tried.

22:20.505 --> 22:22.370
It's been well documented,
all right?

22:22.441 --> 22:23.533
I've read all of them.

22:23.608 --> 22:26.008
- I marked chapters for you.
- Oh, Charlie.

22:26.078 --> 22:28.842
The thing is that nobody realized how special

22:28.914 --> 22:30.245
this Father Torres was.

22:30.349 --> 22:33.841
Nobody ever went and looked
into his background!

22:35.187 --> 22:38.782
Charlie, these people
all look like idiots.

22:45.564 --> 22:46.724
I'm going to go to bed.

22:46.798 --> 22:49.130
- Miranda...
- You're freaking me out.

22:49.234 --> 22:50.462
Okay?

23:05.217 --> 23:06.582
I'm not decent.

23:06.651 --> 23:07.811
Come on, Miranda.
Open up.

23:14.459 --> 23:17.895
Sometimes I wake up and...
and I don't know if I'm me.

23:17.963 --> 23:20.090
That's why you take
your medication.

23:20.165 --> 23:21.826
No, it's not that.
I'm me. I know that.

23:21.933 --> 23:26.336
What I'm saying is that...
I don't know if I exist.

23:26.438 --> 23:28.235
- Oh.
- Come on, listen...

23:28.306 --> 23:30.171
No, I... I'm listening.
You're not sure you exist.

23:30.275 --> 23:32.072
- And?
- I've done a lot of things in my life.

23:32.144 --> 23:34.271
But maybe I haven't
done what I need to do.

23:34.346 --> 23:38.840
And if I do this,
maybe I will.

23:38.950 --> 23:40.281
Exist?

23:40.352 --> 23:41.580
Yeah.

23:43.755 --> 23:46.747
You're shaking.
You need something to eat.

23:46.825 --> 23:48.850
Read the book.

23:48.960 --> 23:50.188
This is so stupid.

23:50.295 --> 23:51.819
Please?

23:55.467 --> 23:57.458
All right, I'll read it
if you eat something.

24:06.678 --> 24:08.009
This is for you.

24:21.326 --> 24:24.784
Parents have this advantage over us.

24:24.863 --> 24:27.388
We want to believe in them.

24:27.499 --> 24:29.694
And when we don't
believe in them,

24:29.801 --> 24:32.634
we still just want
to be with them.

24:49.921 --> 24:50.910
Hey, Padre!

24:51.022 --> 24:52.046
As a young man,

24:52.157 --> 24:54.387
Torres was a mathematics scholar in Seville.

24:56.161 --> 24:58.686
In fact, it looks like he might've
been sent to the New World

24:58.763 --> 25:01.732
because certain of his ideas
were considered heretical.

25:06.771 --> 25:08.739
But that's not
what's important.

25:08.840 --> 25:11.400
The thing that matters here
is that he was more accustomed

25:11.510 --> 25:15.276
to communicating
with numbers than words.

25:15.380 --> 25:17.211
So then, it dawned
on me one night,

25:17.282 --> 25:19.375
while the other patients
were watching JAG.

25:19.451 --> 25:20.748
They like that in there?

25:20.852 --> 25:22.513
- They love it.
- Oh.

25:22.587 --> 25:25.522
Anyway, I noticed that some
of the passages repeated themselves.

25:25.590 --> 25:27.683
I read the book again,
and sure enough they did.

25:27.759 --> 25:31.058
So I began to wonder, why would
somebody in the middle of nowhere

25:31.129 --> 25:34.064
presumably with a limited
supply of pen and ink

25:34.132 --> 25:35.565
repeat themselves like that?

25:35.634 --> 25:37.226
Senility?

25:37.302 --> 25:40.066
He was writing in code.

25:40.138 --> 25:42.538
Took me a long time,
but I finally broke it.

25:46.811 --> 25:48.244
I gotta go.

26:17.776 --> 26:20.404
See, I transposed
Padre Torres' description

26:20.478 --> 26:23.072
and found the area he was
in was exactly seven leagues

26:23.148 --> 26:24.740
to the north of where
he said he was.

26:24.816 --> 26:26.340
It's simple, really.

26:46.471 --> 26:48.939
Charlie believed
the doubloon had been dropped

26:49.007 --> 26:50.941
when Father Torres'
expedition was robbed

26:51.009 --> 26:53.477
and half of his party
was massacred.

26:53.545 --> 26:56.139
He thought that Torres
had headed northwest after that,

26:56.214 --> 26:58.705
and that we were following
the same route.

27:01.620 --> 27:04.680
"Journal of Father
Juan Florismartes Torres,

27:04.789 --> 27:10.284
"18th of October,
the year of our Lord 1624.

27:10.362 --> 27:14.492
"As we reached the summit and look
down into the valley of Santa Clarita,

27:14.566 --> 27:17.057
"there unfolded before us
was as beautiful a picture

27:17.168 --> 27:19.796
"as one ever looked upon.

27:19.871 --> 27:24.035
"We saw a large green meadow
of thousands of acres, more or less,

27:24.142 --> 27:26.633
"its north side bounded
by low mountains at the base

27:26.711 --> 27:29.703
"which oak trees
were plentiful.

27:29.814 --> 27:32.248
"It was like a grand old park,

27:32.350 --> 27:35.547
"such as we read of
in fairy tales.

27:35.654 --> 27:37.849
"We passed that night
under some large trees

27:37.922 --> 27:39.321
"whose branches
went over our heads

27:39.391 --> 27:40.824
"as beautifully
as the ceilings

27:40.892 --> 27:43.884
"in our finest cathedrals.

27:43.995 --> 27:47.396
"Upon our safe arrival, we offered
the sacrament on a large rock

27:47.499 --> 27:51.230
"that seemed almost to have
been fashioned for that holy purpose.

27:51.336 --> 27:52.894
"I bade the smith
use his chisel

27:53.004 --> 27:56.269
"to carve the three crosses
of Golgotha into the stone.

28:01.179 --> 28:05.707
You have arrived
at your destination.

28:05.784 --> 28:07.684
This is it.

28:07.752 --> 28:09.549
- It might be.
- No, it is! It is!

28:09.621 --> 28:11.612
Look how old these trees are.

28:14.292 --> 28:15.759
All right.

28:15.860 --> 28:18.294
So obviously, it's going
to be worn down, right?

28:18.396 --> 28:21.627
I mean, you know,
it's more than 300 years old.

28:21.733 --> 28:23.530
Uh!

28:23.601 --> 28:24.932
Damn!

28:26.404 --> 28:27.735
C- Come here, come here.

28:27.806 --> 28:29.774
- See this?
- What?

28:29.874 --> 28:31.739
This is it.

28:31.810 --> 28:32.936
Look at that.

28:33.044 --> 28:34.739
Look! Look!

28:36.448 --> 28:37.437
I don't know.
It might be.

28:37.549 --> 28:39.483
It is!
That's it!

28:39.584 --> 28:42.314
The rock must've moved.

28:42.420 --> 28:44.650
Well, it could be
an earthquake.

28:49.461 --> 28:51.486
Wait a minute.

28:51.596 --> 28:52.585
Wait a minute.
Look!

28:52.664 --> 28:54.791
I think I see it, right there!

28:54.899 --> 28:56.230
I see it. Look!
Yeah, they're upside-down.

28:56.301 --> 28:57.996
That's why I didn't
recognize them at first.

28:59.471 --> 29:01.166
Can I help you?

29:02.507 --> 29:03.906
I think it's time to go.

29:03.975 --> 29:05.567
Why do they always say,
"Can I help you?"

29:05.643 --> 29:07.235
When it's the last thing
they want to do?

29:07.312 --> 29:08.301
Sir?

29:08.413 --> 29:09.402
And they say "sir"
and "ma'am"

29:09.481 --> 29:10.846
like they want
to show some respect.

29:10.949 --> 29:12.075
- It's monstrous.
- Charlie.

29:12.150 --> 29:13.481
- Sir!
- Yes.

29:13.585 --> 29:16.281
Are you a member
here at La Cresta?

29:18.356 --> 29:19.687
Are you shitting me?

29:19.791 --> 29:21.486
Then I'll have to
ask you to leave.

29:21.593 --> 29:23.527
- Are you happy?
- Sir?

29:23.628 --> 29:25.926
- Charlie.
- All I want to know is are you happy?

29:25.997 --> 29:26.986
Sir.

29:27.098 --> 29:28.963
- Is this man your father?
- Yeah.

29:29.033 --> 29:32.867
Just wanted to see
your eyes.

29:32.971 --> 29:35.997
I couldn't tell
what color they were.

29:36.107 --> 29:38.200
A first, I thought
they were brown.

29:38.309 --> 29:42.006
Now they're looking
very green.

29:42.113 --> 29:44.775
Must be the foliage.

29:44.849 --> 29:47.818
They are so beautiful.

29:50.889 --> 29:51.981
They're hazel.

29:54.392 --> 29:56.292
Hazel.

29:59.998 --> 30:04.731
Well, I'm so sorry that I
caused you any problems.

30:05.904 --> 30:09.067
But... I'll be on my way.

30:14.646 --> 30:16.546
I can't believe you just gave
that cop our phone number.

30:16.648 --> 30:18.673
I hope she calls me.
She's a peach.

30:18.750 --> 30:20.012
Once you get
that flack vest off,

30:20.084 --> 30:21.073
she'd be something else.

30:21.186 --> 30:23.552
Oh, God.

30:26.524 --> 30:28.685
Let's just say this gold does exist.

30:28.760 --> 30:30.887
What are you going to do
with it after you get it?

30:30.995 --> 30:32.895
Wouldn't we have to give it
to a museum or something?

30:32.997 --> 30:34.555
Not necessarily.

30:34.666 --> 30:37.601
I know a lot of people who want
to buy it if we wanted to sell it,

30:37.702 --> 30:39.727
but you're missing the point.

30:39.838 --> 30:40.827
What's that?

30:40.905 --> 30:42.668
I don't want the money.

30:42.740 --> 30:45.709
That's easy for you to say.
You don't have to work for it.

30:45.777 --> 30:48.371
Well, define work.

31:26.317 --> 31:27.875
People walk around all day,

31:27.952 --> 31:30.113
sure that they're going
to win the lottery.

31:30.221 --> 31:32.553
I've always thought
that was crazy.

31:32.624 --> 31:34.717
Ten more minutes, Randy.

31:34.792 --> 31:36.885
My name is Miranda.

31:36.961 --> 31:40.488
At least Charlie had a plan.

31:40.598 --> 31:44.762
I mean, who doesn't
want to believe in buried treasure?

32:00.151 --> 32:04.178
Still, maybe I shouldn't
have encouraged him.

32:35.787 --> 32:37.982
"From the journal
of Father Torres,

32:38.056 --> 32:41.719
"November 21st, 1624.

32:41.826 --> 32:44.886
"The natives appear to be
a simple, good-natured,

32:44.996 --> 32:46.861
"stupid race of people,

32:46.965 --> 32:49.661
"and in most respects
resemble the savages we find

32:49.734 --> 32:52.635
"in other newly-discovered countries.

32:52.704 --> 32:55.332
"There was no sign
of aggression at first,

32:55.406 --> 32:57.636
"until one of the soldiers
who'd come into our mission

32:57.709 --> 32:59.506
"was inspired to the act
of seduction,

32:59.577 --> 33:02.705
"the object being
a young female.

33:02.814 --> 33:04.179
"An action
unfathomable to me

33:04.248 --> 33:08.309
"as the females are uniformly
unpleasant of aspect.

33:08.386 --> 33:10.479
"Considerable uproar ensued
and we were forced

33:10.555 --> 33:14.321
to retreat inland,
following the river upstream."

33:17.562 --> 33:19.860
After they carved
the crosses on the rock,

33:19.931 --> 33:21.558
Father Torres' expedition
had followed

33:21.666 --> 33:23.497
the Santa Clarita River.

33:23.568 --> 33:27.595
The thing was there wasn't
a Santa Clarita River anymore.

33:27.705 --> 33:30.071
It had been dammed
and diverted.

33:30.174 --> 33:32.039
But Charlie thought
that his calculations

33:32.110 --> 33:35.102
would lead us to where
the river used to flow.

33:35.213 --> 33:38.046
He said I can look it up
if I didn't believe him.

33:42.420 --> 33:43.944
What do I say?

33:47.592 --> 33:49.116
You don't have to say anything.

33:49.227 --> 33:52.128
We've got every right
to be here.

33:52.230 --> 33:54.425
Thanks for the tip!

34:00.304 --> 34:01.896
You got a 302 in there?

34:01.973 --> 34:03.440
What?

34:03.541 --> 34:05.065
Does that have a 302 in it?

34:05.143 --> 34:06.303
What?

34:06.411 --> 34:07.400
The backhoe.

34:07.478 --> 34:10.311
Oh, that.
Yeah, yeah.

34:10.415 --> 34:13.873
It's a power plant,
that 302, for its size.

34:13.951 --> 34:15.885
It sure is.

34:19.757 --> 34:21.054
Ha ha!

34:21.125 --> 34:23.491
Ah! Jesus Christ!

34:23.594 --> 34:25.425
Pottery shards!
Ha ha!

34:25.496 --> 34:28.226
Will you excuse me?
I'll catch you later.

34:28.299 --> 34:29.891
Right on.

34:34.105 --> 34:35.402
Broken water jugs,

34:35.473 --> 34:37.907
exactly the same kind
the expedition would've used!

34:37.975 --> 34:40.136
And look, it's even got
curved sides.

34:40.244 --> 34:41.938
Okay, well, shouldn't
we take them to somebody

34:42.013 --> 34:43.241
like an archeologist
or something?

34:43.313 --> 34:44.975
What, have them
spoil everything?

34:45.083 --> 34:47.347
No, they can do that...
that thing, that radio...

34:47.452 --> 34:48.418
- Radio carbon dating, yeah.
- Yeah.

34:49.687 --> 34:51.848
That's been discredited
a long time ago.

34:51.956 --> 34:55.016
"In questions of science
the analysis of a thousand

34:55.126 --> 34:58.687
is not worth the humble reasoning
of a single individual!"

34:58.796 --> 34:59.854
Galileo!

35:01.432 --> 35:04.833
Miranda, just feel this.

35:04.936 --> 35:07.336
Put that in your hands.

35:07.438 --> 35:09.872
Feel how old that is.

35:14.479 --> 35:15.878
Charlie believed
that if we followed

35:15.980 --> 35:18.471
the original riverbed,
we would locate the cavern

35:18.549 --> 35:19.675
where Father Torres
and his men

35:19.784 --> 35:22.947
had been forced
to abandon their gold.

35:23.020 --> 35:25.682
But there was one obstacle.

35:34.665 --> 35:37.225
49.2 degrees north.

35:37.335 --> 35:39.360
This is the way.

35:39.470 --> 35:41.700
Hi. Uh, do you have
your card?

35:41.806 --> 35:43.330
Oh, we're just browsing.

35:50.148 --> 35:52.048
What I need you to do...

35:52.150 --> 35:56.678
I want you to take
this out 67 feet.

35:58.222 --> 35:59.314
Please?

36:20.545 --> 36:22.274
Don't touch that!

36:22.380 --> 36:24.848
Don't...
Oh, Jesus Christ.

36:24.916 --> 36:26.042
I'm so close.

36:26.117 --> 36:28.278
- Excuse me, sir.
- What?

36:28.386 --> 36:30.718
Pardon me, but I didn't know
we really carried these.

36:30.788 --> 36:33.222
These? You guys
got everything in here.

36:33.291 --> 36:35.589
Yeah, we sure do.
Is it working out for you?

36:35.693 --> 36:37.957
- It's working out fine. It's fine.
- Okay.

36:38.062 --> 36:41.190
All right, well...
Okay. All right.

36:50.541 --> 36:52.270
Okay.

36:52.376 --> 36:53.536
All right.

36:53.611 --> 36:56.409
I'll just get this...

36:56.480 --> 36:58.573
- Okay.
- Sighs]

36:58.649 --> 37:00.583
Can you hold this, please?

37:02.820 --> 37:04.151
This is plugged.

37:04.255 --> 37:05.882
This over here.

37:05.957 --> 37:08.050
24 degrees.

37:08.125 --> 37:09.615
And that's it.

37:17.902 --> 37:19.494
X marks the spot.

37:21.806 --> 37:23.398
This is so wild.

37:23.474 --> 37:25.669
Doubloons from
the King of Spain,

37:25.776 --> 37:27.107
lost more than
300 years ago

37:27.178 --> 37:29.942
and they're buried
under a Costco?

37:30.014 --> 37:32.414
Well, I guess you know
it wasn't meant to be.

37:33.484 --> 37:35.111
It's only 6 feet down.

37:36.787 --> 37:38.311
Only 6 feet?

37:38.422 --> 37:39.787
M- Maybe 7.

37:39.857 --> 37:42.018
It'll take two
highly-motivated individuals

37:42.126 --> 37:43.593
maybe fours hours
with the right equipment.

37:43.661 --> 37:46.289
Are you nuts?

37:46.364 --> 37:49.094
I'm sorry, but can we be realistic here?

37:49.166 --> 37:50.690
I'm being realistic.
There's no problem here.

37:50.801 --> 37:53.269
- I'll lay it out.
- No, forget it, Charlie.

37:53.337 --> 37:54.634
No way.

37:54.705 --> 37:56.297
- You did your best.
- No, no, no, no!

37:56.374 --> 37:59.468
I'm not going to be beaten
by a few layers of concrete!

37:59.543 --> 38:01.340
No, sir!
Not on my watch!

38:01.445 --> 38:03.538
Hey, take it easy.

38:56.434 --> 38:59.198
Mom was a hand model,

38:59.270 --> 39:03.707
a job held by adult women
with eerily childlike hands.

39:03.774 --> 39:05.537
Which you don't
come across every day,

39:05.609 --> 39:07.236
so they get paid pretty well.

39:07.345 --> 39:09.711
Cut. Great.
That's a wrap.

39:09.780 --> 39:11.839
She was careful.

39:11.916 --> 39:13.508
She had to be.

39:13.584 --> 39:16.246
Her hands were the only income
we had for a while.

39:16.354 --> 39:18.515
Don't you touch my hands!

39:22.093 --> 39:25.392
After she left, it was just me and Charlie.

39:27.765 --> 39:30.233
Things were a lot more
exciting then.

39:32.403 --> 39:33.961
Like an adventure.

39:36.307 --> 39:38.901
But the supply of toys dwindled.

39:41.145 --> 39:43.045
We managed, though.

39:55.893 --> 39:59.488
I don't know why anybody would
want to buy one of these things.

40:01.565 --> 40:06.127
It's not as if it's so hard
to wash dishes by hand

40:06.237 --> 40:08.467
the old-fashioned way.

40:40.538 --> 40:41.971
Ooh!

40:57.288 --> 40:58.482
Morning.

40:59.557 --> 41:01.354
You...

41:02.560 --> 41:04.391
Uh, Miranda?

41:19.043 --> 41:20.169
What happened to my car?

41:20.244 --> 41:21.506
Miranda...

41:21.579 --> 41:22.910
Did you wreck it?

41:24.815 --> 41:26.806
I couldn't pay the rental
on the backhoe.

41:26.884 --> 41:27.873
No way.

41:27.985 --> 41:30.715
So, your car
was a necessary sacrifice.

41:30.821 --> 41:32.721
But we're almost there,
Miranda.

41:32.823 --> 41:34.552
We are so close.

41:34.658 --> 41:36.717
Jesus Christ.

41:38.829 --> 41:41.059
I'm sorry, I...

41:41.165 --> 41:43.998
I'm really sorry.
I just wasn't thinking.

41:44.068 --> 41:45.160
You never do.

41:45.236 --> 41:47.397
Well, I'll get it back.

41:47.505 --> 41:49.598
- How are you going to do that?
- I don't know.

41:49.707 --> 41:50.696
But I will.

41:50.774 --> 41:52.332
Well, I guess I'd better
get a move on

41:52.409 --> 41:54.172
since I'm going
to have to take the bus.

41:54.245 --> 41:56.042
Can't you get a friend
to give you a ride?

41:56.113 --> 41:58.946
I don't have any friends.

41:59.049 --> 42:02.849
What about that skinny one
who only eats carrots?

42:02.920 --> 42:04.182
Carrots-and-Mountain Dew-Julia?

42:04.255 --> 42:05.745
Right, Julia,
carrots, right.

42:05.856 --> 42:06.880
She had an eating disorder.

42:06.957 --> 42:09.585
She went to the hospital
and died.

42:09.693 --> 42:11.217
Oh.

42:11.295 --> 42:13.855
Well, in that case, maybe I can
go back down and get the car.

42:13.931 --> 42:15.057
I'm sure he hasn't
sold it yet.

42:15.132 --> 42:17.100
It wasn't that the car
was in such great shape.

42:17.201 --> 42:19.431
- I'm sure the car...
- Stop! Stop!

42:19.537 --> 42:20.936
I loved that car.

42:21.038 --> 42:22.733
I know you did.

42:22.806 --> 42:24.569
No, you didn't
because I never told you.

42:24.642 --> 42:26.041
Why? Because you never listen.

42:26.110 --> 42:28.943
All right, I'm an asshole.
That has been established.

42:29.046 --> 42:32.413
Not to the extent that
I'm about to establish it.

42:32.483 --> 42:35.418
You make fun of everything
I do, including my job.

42:35.486 --> 42:37.044
No, I'm proud of you working.

42:37.121 --> 42:38.281
Don't... Yeah, right.

42:38.389 --> 42:39.981
You know, I'm the one
that's paying the bills.

42:40.090 --> 42:42.615
No, it's wild.
Isn't it?

42:43.827 --> 42:46.057
You don't take anything seriously, do you?

42:46.130 --> 42:48.963
You think the world
is just here for your amusement.

42:49.066 --> 42:51.159
- Look at the world.
- I do.

42:51.268 --> 42:54.135
But unlike you,
I have to live in it.

42:54.238 --> 42:57.071
I just...
I don't understand.

42:57.141 --> 42:58.506
You're a really smart guy.

42:58.609 --> 43:01.942
How can you keep
doing this year after year?

43:02.012 --> 43:04.742
What do you mean?

43:04.815 --> 43:08.273
The treasure is just like
all your jazz combos, Charlie.

43:08.352 --> 43:10.411
Just like the tour boat
that sank,

43:10.487 --> 43:13.479
just like the Mexican
holistic medical degree,

43:13.591 --> 43:15.855
just like your marriage.

43:15.960 --> 43:17.825
How come you can't
see that?

43:17.928 --> 43:21.329
Everybody else can.

43:21.432 --> 43:24.162
There's something
really wrong with you.

43:32.209 --> 43:35.440
I can't believe
you sold my fucking car!

43:35.512 --> 43:36.706
And now... Oh.

43:38.482 --> 43:43.385
And now, I give you
Orange Grove Estates' 1,000th family.

43:43.487 --> 43:45.182
Let's give them a hand.

